    5259             : /*
    5260             : Determine whether a function is viable in overload resolution, which
    5261             : means whether it has the right number of parameters of the right
    5262             : types.  proj_function_symbol indicates the function; it may be a
    5263             : projection symbol, but it is not an overloaded function.
    5264             : overloaded_function_symbol is the overloaded function symbol that gave
    5265             : rise to proj_function_symbol; it also may be a projection symbol, or
    5266             : the same symbol as proj_function_symbol, or it may be NULL if it
    5267             : doesn't apply (e.g., when proj_function_symbol is a conversion
    5268             : function).  is_template_id is TRUE if the symbol has an associated
    5269             : explicit template argument list; if so, template_arg_list gives the
    5270             : argument list.  If surrogate_function_conv_sym is non-NULL, we are
    5271             : evaluating a surrogate function call (see [over.call.object] in the
    5272             : C++ standard); proj_function_symbol is NULL and routine_type gives the
    5273             : function type.  The argument list for the call is given by
    5274             : arg_list, and the selector is given by bound_function_selector
    5275             : (if have_selector is TRUE).  have_selector can be TRUE and
    5276             : bound_function_selector NULL when calling constructors.
    5277             : bound_function_selector is an object pointer if
    5278             : bound_function_selector->selector_is_object_pointer is TRUE, an object
    5279             : otherwise.  implicit_selector_type indicates the type of an implicit
    5280             : "this->" selector, if applicable, or is NULL otherwise.  Any viable
    5281             : functions are added to the candidate_functions list along with
    5282             : information on the level of argument matches.  If a match would have
    5283             : been found except for the absence of a selector, set
    5284             : *matched_except_for_missing_selector TRUE, and if a match would have
    5285             : been found except for a mismatch on the selector, set
    5286             : *matched_except_for_selector TRUE; those allow different error
    5287             : messages.  If ctor_conversion_case is TRUE, this analysis is being
    5288             : done as part of resolving an implicit or explicit conversion to a
    5289             : class type: the functions are constructors, have_selector is FALSE
    5290             : (sic; the "this" parameter is not matched up); the "conversion" field
    5291             : is set in any candidate function entries created.
    5292             : effects_copy_initialization is TRUE if this call is the user-defined
    5293             : conversion in a copy-initialization; constructors that are marked
    5294             : "explicit" are ignored.  allow_udc_on_arguments is TRUE if
    5295             : user-defined conversions should be allowed on the argument matches.
    5296             : arg_dep_lookup_done is TRUE if argument-dependent lookup is enabled
    5297             : for this call.  from_arg_dep_lookup is TRUE if the function was found
    5298             : by argument-dependent lookup.  dependent_call is TRUE if the call is a
    5299             : template-dependent call.  known_to_be_visible is TRUE if the function
    5300             : is known to be visible and the visibility check should be suppressed.
    5301             : is_overloaded_operator is TRUE if the call is written in operator
    5302             : form, e.g., a+b rather than operator+(a, b).
    5303             : allow_post_declared_functions is TRUE if functions declared after the
    5304             : point of reference in a dependent call should be visible to the normal
    5305             : lookup (in violation of the requirements of the standard).
    5306             : *discarded_because_post_decl goes along with that: it is returned TRUE

    6023             : static void try_overloaded_function_match(
    6024             :                  a_symbol_ptr             overloaded_function_symbol,
    6025             :                  a_boolean                is_template_id,
    6026             :                  a_template_arg_ptr       template_arg_list,
    6027             :                  an_arg_list_elem_ptr     arg_list,
    6028             :                  an_arg_list_elem_ptr     init_list_ctor_arg_list,
    6029             :                  a_boolean                have_selector,
    6030             :                  an_operand               *bound_function_selector,
    6031             :                  a_boolean                ctor_conversion_case,
    6032             :                  a_boolean                effects_copy_initialization,
    6033             :                  a_boolean                allow_udc_on_arguments,
    6034             :                  a_boolean                arg_dep_lookup_done,
    6035             :                  a_boolean                from_arg_dep_lookup,
    6036             :                  a_boolean                dependent_call,
    6037             :                  a_boolean                forced_dependent,
    6038             :                  a_boolean                ignore_templates,
    6039             :                  a_boolean                known_to_be_visible,
    6040             :                  a_boolean                is_overloaded_operator,
    6041             :                  a_conv_context_set       conv_context,
    6042             :                  a_candidate_function_ptr *candidate_functions,
    6043             :                  a_symbol_ptr             *inaccessible_match,
    6044             :                  a_boolean                *matched_except_for_missing_selector,
    6045             :                  a_boolean                *matched_except_for_selector)
    6046             : /*
    6047             : Find out how well the functions described by overloaded_function_symbol
    6048             : match the argument list given by arg_list and the selector given
    6049             : (if have_selector is TRUE) by bound_function_selector.  have_selector
    6050             : can be TRUE and bound_function_selector NULL when calling constructors.
    6051             : overloaded_function_symbol may be an overloaded function, a simple
    6052             : function, or a projection symbol for one of those.  is_template_id
    6053             : is TRUE if the symbol has an associated explicit template argument list;
    6054             : if so, template_arg_list gives the argument list.
    6055             : bound_function_selector is an object pointer if
    6056             : bound_function_selector->selector_is_object_pointer is TRUE, an object
    6057             : otherwise.  Any viable functions are added to the candidate_functions
    6058             : list along with information on the level of argument matches.  If a
    6059             : match would have been found except for the absence of a selector, set
    6060             : *matched_except_for_missing_selector TRUE, and if a match would have
    6061             : been found except for a mismatch on the selector, set
    6062             : *matched_except_for_selector TRUE; those allow different error
    6063             : messages.  If inaccessible_match is non-NULL, in C++/CLI mode it will
    6064             : be set to a symbol that would have been chosen except that it was

   13711             :     need_lvalue_result is TRUE (but see ref_binding_type, below), or
   13712             : (b) a built-in type in the set given by builtin_types_allowed, if
   13713             :     builtin_types_allowed != BTK_NONE, and a non-const lvalue of that
   13714             :     type if need_lvalue_result is TRUE (if both (a) and (b) apply,
   13715             :     (b) takes precedence, and dest_type is used only to guide the
   13716             :     selection of template conversion functions and to establish the
   13717             :     cost of any conversion needed after the conversion function).
   13718             : 
   13719             : If only a source type, and not a source operand, is available,
   13720             : it can be indicated by passing it as source_type, and source_operand
   13721             : will be ignored.
   13722             : 
   13723             : Usually, this routine is called for standard conversion functions and
   13724             : source_operand has a class type.  However, in C++/CLI, conv_funcs_class
   13725             : can be non-NULL to specify the class in which we should look for
   13726             : conversion functions.  In particular, when cppcli_atypical_case is TRUE
   13727             : we are looking for C++/CLI static conversion functions declared
   13728             : in the class identified by conv_funcs_class, and the source or
   13729             : destination type will be a managed class or a handle to a managed
   13730             : class (or reference to a managed class, for the destination type).
   13731             : Note that static conversion functions that can do a "normal"
   13732             : conversion from their class to another type are considered on calls
   13733             : with cppcli_atypical_case FALSE and not on calls with
   13734             : cppcli_atypical_case TRUE.  However, one can also specify
   13735             : only_std_funcs TRUE to specify that only standard (nonstatic)
   13736             : conversion functions should be considered.
   13737             : 
   13738             : In the case of a bitwise copy constructor, dest_type reflects the parameter
   13739             : type of the constructor, which can be different from the type actually
   13740             : specified in a cast; requested_type gives the original type and is used to
   13741             : ensure that argument deduction for a conversion function template will use
   13742             : the type actually specified rather than the constructor's parameter type.
   13743             : (In all other cases, dest_type and requested_type should be the same.)
   13744             :

   13746             : evaluate how well it matches the arguments and add it to the
   13747             : candidate_functions list, setting "conversion" in the candidate
